            <p class="header">"This" : Ferrofluid Playful Box</p>

            <p class="header">Sensor Research</p>
            <p>
                <i>
                    Visit any electronic suppliers’ website and do a catalogue search for at least three interesting over-the-counter ANALOG sensors. Document the specifications of these three sensors i.e. voltage requirements, resistance, sampling value ranges etc., along with how these sensors are used with the Arduino and any special requirements to utilise the sensor(s) i.e. external libraries.
                    </br></br>
                    Then, choose at least one of the researched ANALOG sensors that could be incorporated into your Assignment 2 – the selected ANALOG sensor(s) would be used as INPUT. Finally, propose and provide storyboards for three possible interaction scenarios that would use these sensor(s).
                </i>
            </p>
            </br>
            <p>
                <b>LV-MaxSonar EZ Sensor</b>
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/research-sonar.jpg">
                    <img src="images/research-sonar.jpg" style="width: 20%;"></img>
                </a>
                <a href="images/research-sonar-2.png">
                    <img src="images/research-sonar-2.png"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                With 2.5V - 5.5V power the LV-MaxSonar-EZ provides very short to long-range detection and ranging in a very small package. The LV-MaxSonar-EZ detects objects from 0-inches to 254-inches (6.45-meters) and provides sonar range information from 6-inches out to 254-inches with 1-inch resolution. Objects from 0-inches to 6-inches typically range as 6-inches1. The interface output formats included are pulse width output, analog voltage output, and RS232 serial output. Factory calibration and testing is completed with a flat object.
                </br></br>
                - Continuously variable gain for control and side lobe suppression</br>
                - Object detection to zero range objects 2.5V to 5.5V supply with 2mA typical current draw</br>
                - Readings can occur up to every 50mS, (20-Hz rate)</br>
                - Free run operation can continually measure and output range information</br>
                - Triggered operation provides the range reading as desired</br>
                - Interfaces are active simultaneously</br>
                - Serial, 0 to Vcc, 9600 Baud, 81N</br>
                - Analog, (Vcc/512) / inch</br>
                - Pulse width, (147uS/inch)</br>
                </br>
                Find out more in its <a href="http://www.maxbotix.com/documents/LV-MaxSonar-EZ_Datasheet.pdf">datasheet</a>.
            </p>
            </br></br>
            <p>
                <b>Electrocardiography (ECG) Sensor</b>
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/research-ecg.png">
                    <img src="images/research-ecg.png" style="width:30%;"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                Heartbeats are triggered by bioelectrical signals of very low amplitude generated by aspecial set of cells in the heart (the  SA node). Electrocardiography (ECG) enables the translation of theseelectrical signalsinto numerical values, enabling them to be used in a wide array of applications. Our sensor allow data acquisitionnot only at the chest (“on-the-person”), but also at the hand palms (“off-the-person”), and works both with pre-gelled and most types of dry electrodes. The bipolar configuration is ideal for low noisedata acquisition.
                </br></br>
                - Gain: 1100</br>
                - Range: ±1.5mV (with VCC = 3.3V)</br>
                - Bandwidth: 0.5-40Hz</br>
                - Consumption: ~0.17mA</br>
                - InputVoltageRange: 2.0-3.5V</br>
                - Input Impedance: 7.5GOhm</br>
                - CMRR: 86dB</br>
                </br>
                Find out more in its <a href="http://bitalino.com/datasheets/REVOLUTION_ECG_Sensor_Datasheet.pdf">datasheet</a>.
            </p>
            </br>
            <p>
                <b>Biomedical Sensor Pad</b>
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/research-biomedical.jpg">
                    <img src="images/research-biomedical.jpg" style="width:20%"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                This is a 10 pack of Biomedical Sensor Pads, disposable electrodes that can be used to measure EEG, ECG and EMG levels. these little pads are perfect for short-term monitoring of Neurofeedback and Biofeedback purposes. They are to be used once and are very handy because of integrated, latex-free gel. Each pad adheres very well to the skin and the snap connector can be pushed on or removed from the electrode lead with no issue.
                </br></br>
                - Backing material : Polyethylene foam (PE), white</br>
                - Adhesive characteristics : Medical grade pressure sensitive adhesive</br>
                - Gel characteristics : Conductive and adhesive hydrogel</br>
                - Supporting / back : label Polypropylene film (PP) transparent</br>
                - Release liner : Polyethylene film (PE), one side siliconized</br>
                - Sensor Polymer Ag/AgCl : coated</br>
                - Adapter / connector : Stainless stee</br>
                </br></br>
                - ACZ I impedance (before defibrillation simulation) : 220 Ohm</br>
                - DC offset voltage (before defibrillation simulation) : 0.2 mV</br>
                - SDR (remaining potential after defibrillation simulation) : 11 mV</br>
                - Slope (potential decline after defibrillation simulation) : 0.2 mV/s</br>
                - COIIN (combined offset instability and inner noise) : 4 µV</br>
                - Bias current tolerance (DC offset voltage after DC loading) : 6 mV</br>
                </br>
                Find out more in its <a href="https://cdn.sparkfun.com/datasheets/Sensors/Biometric/H124SG.pdf">datasheet</a>.
            </p>       

            <p class="header">Concept</p>
            <p>
                <i>
                - It must use at least one ANALOG sensor as the PRIMARY INPUT.</br>
                - You may incorporate digital sensors to aid in functional requirements of your object</br>
                - The objects’ output follows your design objectives</br>
                - You must use the Arduino to process your data input to output</br>
                - You may keep the circuit on a breadboard as long as it can be incorporated neatly into your object</br>
                - Bring it to class for a live demo on the due date.</br>
                </i>
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/concept-1.jpg">
                    <img src="images/concept-1.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                Magnetism is an invisble force which omnipresent in our world and it is tighly coupled with electricity creating a Electromagnetism which is one of four fundamental forces found in nature.
                </br></br>
                I decided to explore it by creating an interactive installation involving Ferrofluid which is a liquid made of nanoscale ferromagnetic particles suspended in a carrier fluid. Ferrofluid was invented in 1963 by NASA's Steve Papell as a liquid rocket fuel that could be drawn toward a pump inlet in a weightless environment by applying a magnetic field. It is used in many other domains including electronics for hard drives and loud speakers.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/concept-2.jpg">
                    <img src="images/concept-2.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I got myself a science exploration kit found in <i>Magnet Montreal</i> shop with a strong magnet.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/concept-3.jpg">
                    <img src="images/concept-3.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I used the magnet to measure the liquid reaction distance - ~2cm.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/concept-4.jpg">
                    <img src="images/concept-4.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                From this point, the hardest part was to find its usage. I setteled on using the Sonar movement sensor as an Analog input but how to bind it to the ferrofluid? I dind't want to immitate what was already done. It led me to explore local grossaries shops to look for items that could incorporate the Ferrofluid inside them. I found two photo frames and miniature plastic masks.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/concept-5.jpg">
                    <img src="images/concept-5.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                It inspired me to create a frame with the ferrofluid inside it which would hide a face and when someone approaches, it reveals either this white mask or a mirror reflection of yourself. I dropped the idea of the mask because even if I integrated it inside, making pass the ferrofluid just through holes in the eyes or around would neccessitate greate control on the magnetic field which in turn would require a complex motor behind to move the magnets. Since the timeframe for this project was quite short, I decided to attempt to create a frame made of ferrofluid with a liquid inside a transparent . The latter would allow me to either place a mirror, nothing or anything else behind the ferrofluid frame. The dark frame reminded me of the Evil Queen's Magic Mirror from the Snow White tale. This made it even more conceptually interesting.
            </p>

            <p class="header">Design</p>
            <p>
                <i>
                    Create an object that changes over time! The same change can occur very quickly (milliseconds) or very slowly (many days) and thus bear very different meanings & create different experiences.
                </i>
            </p>
            </br>
            <p>
                I extracted the glass from each frames and they almost fitted into the frame for the ferrofluid.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-1.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-1.jpg"></img>
                </a>
                <a href="images/design-2.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-2.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                The little oversize could be cut. This led me to explore the Wood Shop on the Concordia 8th EV floor. This place turned out being very interesting. They helped me by teaching how to cut the glass and I even found some free wood leftovers perfect for my frame container. I think it's better to create a complete object containing the circuits inside.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-3.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-3.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                Thanks to Alexander Charette for the Plexiglass.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-4.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-4.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I decided to use this setup to create a box inside which one can look to explore the ferrofluid reacting to its hand gestures detected by the Sonar sensor. Since, the box may be large, a horizontal layout looked more attractive than the vertical one. It would allow a user to place it anywhere in its house without trying to place it on walls at its eyes level to prevent uncomfortable bending. Plus, a vertical one would force the ferrofluid down by the earth's gravity force which would make it more hard to attract it from the bottom using magnets, without saying that all of the electronics would need to be fixed on wall inside the box. Therefore, I went with the horizontal box layout.
                </br></br>
                To seal the frame I used the Wood Shop recommendation of using water-proof Silicon :
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-5.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-5.jpg"></img>
                </a>
                <a href="images/design-6.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-6.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I applied it generously as it takes 24h to dry and since there are two sides it is a minimum of 48h. This is stressful situation because if it failes, it may also fail a second time unless the exact reason were to be found. During this waiting period, I started to think about the plan B in case this frame container would not work and I went into searching for ferrofluid solution.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-8.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-8.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                According to my research a water with a saturation of sugar should work. I tested it before to make sure and it seemed okay. The normal water is on left and the sugar water on the right :
            </p>
            </br>
            <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/187931840" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </br>
            <p>
                As soon as the Silicon was dried, I put some water inside to ensure it is sealed. To my relief, it sealed just fine. I decided to put some water with a saturation of sugar and fill it partially with the ferrofluid.
            </p>
            </br>
            <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/187972561" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </br>
            <p>
                Then, I sealed the other side of the frame.
                </br></br>
                Let the second 24h beggin!
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-10.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-10.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
               Once the time have passed, I decided to test the result :
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-11.png">
                    <img src="images/design-11.png"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
               Obviously something didn't worked as expected... :'(
               </br></br>
               Maybe the water didn't reached saturation of sugar or the ferrofluid had a too long exposure to oxygen or maybe the sillicon has its part in it. Bottom line, this didn't worked.
                </br></br>
                I decided to keep my focus on the rest of the installation and go to the Concordia's Wood Shop. 
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/design-19.jpg">
                    <img src="images/design-19.jpg"></img>
