            <p class="header">Circuit</p>
            <p>
                To move the magnet, I used the <a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/products/10976">Slide Pot</a> motorized slider with a combination of a H-Bridge to control its direction by altering a Direct Current :
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/circuit-1.jpg">
                    <img src="images/circuit-1.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I found an online schematic of this motor :
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/circuit.jpg">
                    <img src="images/circuit.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                However, I discovered that the analog pin didn't worked by only showing its 0 - 1023 values range on the 20% of the slider. I debuged this issue for quite some time. I even tried to weld all of the pins to wires and trying altering them all :
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/circuit-0.jpg">
                    <img src="images/circuit-0.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                Still, no success on finding the right analog pin.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/circuit-2.jpg">
                    <img src="images/circuit-2.jpg"></img>
                </a>
            </div>

            <p class="header">Arduino Code</p>
            <p>
                The fact that the analog pin didn't worked as expected made it impossible to map the sensor movements to the motor ones to create a direct binding between hand motions and ferrofluid mouvement. Therefore, I fallback on the automatic movement all the way into one of the two slider's directions after any detected motions within certain proximity.
            </p>
            <div class="images">
                <a href="images/code-1.png">
                    <img src="images/code-1.png"></img>
                </a>
                <a href="images/code-2.png">
                    <img src="images/code-2.png"></img>
                </a>
            </div>
            <p>
                I didn't went into fancy code with polishing because of the time constraints. Plus, it turned out that the sonar library wasn't working as well as their code examples. I used a rules to find out that the division by 8 gave me the most accurate value for sonar distance in inches.
                </br></br>
                You can get this code <a href="arduino-code.ino">here</a>.
            </p>

            <p class="header">In Action</p>
            <p>
                Due to the black frame unsuccessful liquid result, I went with the idea of creating a support to suspend any kind of ferrofuid containers. Thus, allowing user to chose to suspend anything else in the wood frame wires and control the magnetic field with hand gestures. Here is the final setup :
            </p>
